
The final game title for our project is **“Cyber Shield: Spot the Phishing Scam.”** The final cyber safety topic focuses on phishing scams, fake emails, suspicious links, and overall online scam awareness. We selected this topic because phishing scams are a very common online threat that can steal personal information and cause serious harm. By learning about these risks early, children can stay safer while using the internet.

This topic is suitable for our target audience, which is children aged 10–12 years old. At this age, students are starting to use emails, websites, and online games more frequently, so they need to understand basic online dangers in a simple and engaging way. Our game is designed to make learning fun while also building awareness about cyber safety.

Through this game, players will learn how to identify fake emails and suspicious links, how to make safe decisions when using the internet, and how to protect their personal information to avoid online scams.

The game is designed for school students aged 10–12 years old. These are young learners who use the internet regularly for studying, playing games, watching videos, and communicating with others. At this age, they are still developing their understanding of online safety, so they need guidance to recognize and avoid cyber risks.

Many children in this age group use online platforms every day, but they may not fully understand threats such as phishing scams, fake messages, suspicious links, and other online dangers. Because of this, they can easily become targets of scams without realizing it.

